===Etymology 1===
<div style="float:right;">
{{wp|ja:カエル}}
{{wp|Frog}}
[[File:Agalychnis callidryas.jpg|thumb|250px|{{m|ja|蛙|tr=kaeru, kawazu, kairu}}: a '''[[frog]]'''.]]
</div>
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|かえる|alt=蛤,蝦}}

{{IPAfont|&#42;⟨kape₁ru⟩}}<!-- Cannot find details on the 甲・乙 value of the /e/ vowel --> → {{IPAchar|/kaperu/}} → {{IPAchar|/kaferu/}} → {{IPAchar|/kaweru/}} → {{IPAchar|/kajeru/}} → {{IPAchar|/kaeru/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=かえる|-}}.

The Nihon Kokugo Daijiten cites this to the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720, however, that may only be traceable to supplemental glosses added later to the ''[[kanbun]]'' original.<ref>{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2|蛙・蛤・蝦}}</ref>

Spelled phonetically once in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'', completed some time after 759 {{CE}}, where it is used phonetically to spell the name of the [[maple]] tree, {{m|ja|楓|tr=kape₁rute > kaede}}.<ref name="JDBkapyeru">{{R:JDB|p=215}}</ref><ref>{{RQ:Manyoshu|8|1623}}</ref>  Generally regarded as the informal or everyday term for {{m|en|frog}}, in contrast to the formal or poetic term ''kawazu'' (see below).<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

The ultimate derivation is unclear, with numerous theories.  Some of the leading ideas include:
* Cognate with {{m|ja|帰る||tr=kaeru|to return (to a point of origin)}}, from the way that some species of frogs return to their birthplace to [[spawn]]
* Cognate with {{m|ja|孵る||tr=kaeru|to hatch (from an egg)}}, in reference to [[tadpole]]s
* Derived from [[onomatopoeia]], where ''kape'' originally referred to the [[frog]]'s [[call]], suffixed uncertain element ''-ru''

The phonetic development went through a clear stage where the middle mora was pronounced {{IPAchar|/je/}}, as illustrated in the 1603 ''{{w|Nippo Jisho}}'' entry, spelled ''cayeru''.<ref>{{R:Nippo Jisho original}}, text [https://books.google.com/books?id=TFJAAQAAMAAJ&pg=PP101 here] towards the bottom of the right-hand column</ref>  This was likely a result of the {{w|Muromachi period}} sound shift, where {{IPAchar|/we/}} shifted to {{IPAchar|/je/}}, followed later by {{IPAchar|/je/}} merging into {{IPAchar|/e/}} to produce modern {{IPAchar|/kaeru/}}.

Now the most common term for {{m|en|frog}}.

